{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658743"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20816"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20816"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.55,0.14,0.18,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12466"},{"type":"tags","id":"12499"},{"type":"tags","id":"12648"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman with HIV infection presents with recurrent oral thrush despite appropriate antifungal treatment. Her CD4+ T-cell count is 150 cells/\u03bcL. The pathophysiology of her susceptibility to fungal infection is being considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the immune response to Candida albicans infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Filamentous forms induce stronger dendritic cell activation","\u03b2-1,3-glucan binding to dectin promotes Th17 responses","Th2 responses are essential for mucosal protection","Yeast forms primarily activate B-cell antibody production","Neutrophil recruitment occurs independently of T-cell activity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003E\u03b2-1,3-glucan binding to dectin promotes Th17 responses\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E yeast forms express \u03b2-1,3-glucan on their surface, which binds to dectin receptors on dendritic cells. This interaction triggers the production of cytokines such as IL-6 and IL-23, which are crucial for promoting Th17 cell development. Th17 cells then coordinate the recruitment of neutrophils and monocytes to the site of infection, which are essential for controlling \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYeast forms primarily activate B-cell antibody production\u003C/strong\u003E - While antibodies may play a role in immunity against \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E, the primary protective response involves cell-mediated immunity through Th17 cells, not humoral immunity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFilamentous forms induce stronger dendritic cell activation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect; the yeast forms of \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E actually activate dendritic cells more strongly than the filamentous forms.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETh2 responses are essential for mucosal protection\u003C/strong\u003E - Th17 responses, not Th2 responses, are the critical T-cell response for protection against mucocutaneous candidiasis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil recruitment occurs independently of T-cell activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Neutrophil recruitment in response to \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E infection is dependent on Th17 cell activity, which produces cytokines that attract these cells to the site of infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s susceptibility to recurrent candidiasis is explained by her low CD4+ T-cell count due to HIV infection, which impairs the development of protective Th17 responses. Similarly, individuals with inherited defects in Th17 cell development also experience recurrent mucocutaneous candidiasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Candida albicans yeast forms activate dendritic cells through \u03b2-1,3-glucan binding to dectin receptors, promoting Th17 responses.","Th17 responses are critical for protection against Candida albicans infection by recruiting neutrophils and monocytes.","Defects in Th17 cell development or low T-cell counts (as in HIV infection) lead to recurrent mucocutaneous candidiasis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 383-384."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20816"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:15:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:16:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":